  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing robust internal control systems\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n- Training employees on AML procedures\n\n4. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Preserving documentation for specified periods\n- Ensuring information is accessible to regulators\n\n5. Risk Management\n- Developing comprehensive AML policies\n- Screening customers against prohibited lists\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\n6. International Compliance\n- Adhering to global AML standards\n- Collaborating with international regulatory bodies\n- Following guidelines from organizations like FATF\n\nFailure to comply can result in significant legal penalties, financial sanctions, and potential criminal prosecution.",
